===Etymology===
{{IPAfont|/omo<sub>2</sub>pu/}} → {{IPAchar|/omwopoju/}} → {{IPAchar|/omwoɸoju/}} → {{IPAchar|/omoɸoju/}} → {{IPAchar|/oboɸoju/}} → {{IPAchar|/oboju/}} → {{IPAchar|/obojuru/}} → {{IPAchar|/obojeru/}} → {{IPAchar|/oboeru/}}

Ultimately from {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=おぼえる|-}} verb {{m|ja|思ふ|tr=omopu|pos=modern {{m|ja|思う}} ''omou'', “to think (about or of something)”}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref> The historical derivation is roughly as follows:
* the {{m|ja|未然形|tr=mizenkei||irrealis form}} ''omopa'' of {{inh|ja|ojp|-|sort=おぼえる}} verb {{m|ja|思ふ|tr=omopu||think|pos=modern {{m|ja|思う}} ''omou''}} + {{m|ja|ゆ|tr=yu|pos={{cog|ojp|-}} verb suffix denoting intransitive, spontaneous, or passive action}}:
: ''omopayu'' → ''omopoyu''
: The {{m|ojp|思ほゆ|tr=omopoyu}} form is found in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' and the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}''.
* [[contraction]] and regular sound changes:
: ''omopoyu'' → ''omofoyu'' → ''obowoyu'' → ''oboyu''
: This change is already evident by the early {{w|Heian period}}.
* regular historical grammatical shifts occurring for classical {{m|ja|下二段活用|tr=shimo nidan katsuyō||lower bigrade conjugation}} verbs:
: ''oboyu'' → ''oboyuru'' → ''oboyeru'' → ''oboeru''
: This set of shifts occurred during the [[w:Kamakura period|Kamakura]] and [[w:Muromachi period|Muromachi]] periods.

The verb was originally used in intransitive and passive contexts, in accordance with its derivation. It began to be used in more active and transitive contexts starting from roughly the mid-{{w|Heian period}}, with the {{m|en|learn}} and {{m|en|memorize}} senses appearing in the {{w|Kamakura period}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

